    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_range_function",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Range Function",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `range()` function creates a sequence of numbers. It's very useful for creating loops that run a specific number of times."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Instead of manually creating counters and conditions, `range()` gives you a clean way to generate numbers for counting."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "basic_range",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Basic Range",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The simplest way to use `range()` is with one number: `range(5)`. This creates numbers from 0 to 4 (5 numbers total)."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`list()` is a function that converts a range into a list of numbers for printing. We will cover **lists** in more detail in later sections."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = range(5)\nprint(list(numbers))",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "[0, 1, 2, 3, 4]"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Notice that `range(5)` gives you 5 numbers starting from 0, so it goes from 0 to 4, not 1 to 5."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "range_with_start_stop",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can specify where to start and where to stop with `range(start, stop)`. The range includes the `start` number but stops before the `stop` number, so the `stop` number is not included."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = range(2, 7)\nprint(list(numbers))",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "[2, 3, 4, 5, 6]"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`range(2, 7)` starts at 2 and stops before 7, so it includes `2, 3, 4, 5, 6` but not `7`."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "range_with_step",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can also specify the step size with `range(start, stop, step)`."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The **step** decides how much to add (or subtract) each time. For example, a step of 2 counts by twos. If you use a negative step, it counts backward."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Counting by 2s**"
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = range(0, 10, 2)\nprint(list(numbers))",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "[0, 2, 4, 6, 8]"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Counting backwards**"
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = range(5, 0, -1)\nprint(list(numbers))",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "[5, 4, 3, 2, 1]"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
